EPODE VIII.

Previous to the general engagement at Actium, there had been several partial engagements between the forces of Augus- tus and Antony, in which fortune favoured the former. Horace, therefore, on hearing of that great battle, which he expected would prove decisive, addressed this epode to his patron Maece- nas, then at the scene of action, in anticipation of the glorious result he predicted to his friend.
